This Dad Played 810 Holes in One Dayand Crushed a World Record Doing It

Kyle Cokinos took 2,800 swings, ran 92 miles, thought he saw a bearand thinks youre capable of more than you think.
  • Author:
    Greg Presto
  • Jul 31, 2025 7:08 PM EDT

Around 5:45 a.m. on June 24, moments after making a putt on the 9th green at Houstons East River 9, Kyle Cokinos yelled out to his wife: He wanted a pile of three-napkin cheeseburgers, a pizza, and a mountain of fries.

Not your normal pre-dawn fare. But Cokinos wasnt having a normal day: The putt hed just sunk was his 423rd make of the day, finishing his 47th nine-hole round in less than 12 hours. And he was planning to tee off more than 400 times before 6 p.m., clocking in 92 miles of running along the way.

The back of my knee (understand knee pain at Aleve) was throbbing with every step. My stomach was just churning. It felt like I was constantly holding down vomit, he says. And you have to remind yourself what youre doing this for.

The Long Road Started on the Range

Cokinos is 31 years old. The father of two has conquered the Grindstone 100, a century run through the Shenandoah Mountains thats considered the East Coasts toughest ultramarathon (learn to go further with Liquid I.V.). Hes crossed the finish line at the Starvation Triathlon, a self-supported Ironman that climbs 12,000 feet during its 120-mile bike leg. And hes world-class in Hyrox, the fitness race thats become one of the worlds fastest-growing sports. At the 2025 World Championships in Chicago, he and his partner, Kara Hoffman, finished 57th in their age group.

But before any of that, the Houston man was a high school golfer gunning for a scholarship.

I would hit range balls for hours and hours every day in the summer, and I wouldnt even pay attention to the heat. I just wanted to be a college golfer, he says. I probably put 10,000 hours into the game, and thenI didnt play college golf.

Cokinos traded his dedication on the greens to one that required gels, throwing himself into the fitness pursuits that would fuel his YouTube following of 10,000 subscribers. While he collected race medals, his clubs collected dust.

Then, in 2021, a friend opened the East River 9, a public, par-3 course just steps from downtown Houston. Cokinos got the itch to pitch and puttbut in a different way than hed done as a high schooler.

I had this old pastime of golf that Id acquired all this skill for, and then I had what I was currently good at, which was running and endurance, he says. In January 2024, Cokinos started tinkering with the idea of golfing all day and nightthe kind of dream you might see on a bumper stickerto combine the two skills into a challenge made for him.

He started with a test run: In July 2024, he played the East River 9 from sunrise to sunset, playing through recreational golfers for round after round, racking up strokes and raising money for Memorial Hermann Hospital in Houston. As the sun dipped below the Texas horizon, Cokinos hatched a plan: A year later, hed go for the recordthe most golf-packed day in history.

Training for Hundreds of Hacks and Hyroxat the Same Time

He wasnt the first to think of it. The previous record holder, former MLB outfielder Eric Byrnes, had played 420 holes in 24 hours in 2019.

Cokinos had his sights set on a much bigger number.

If conditions were right, I knew I could get to 800, or potentially 900 holes, he says. That confidence came, in part, because he thought of the challenge as akin to Hyrox. In the fitness race, which has become one of the worlds fastest-growing sports, Cokinos and other competitors stop and start, running from one fitness challengea lift, a session on a Concept2 ski erg, or another challengebefore picking up and running again.

In my mind, this was the same thing, just for a much longer durationwith the stations a lot closer, and having to do a lot more stations.

Inside Hunter McIntyres Nutrition Strategy: How the 3-Time Hyrox Champ Handles Cravings and Calories
Read More

While Hyrox had him feeling mentally prepared, Cokinos knew hed need to train physically: To complete the record, hed need to take thousands of swings, taxing his hands, back, trunk, and shoulders with each twist. But he couldnt abandon his Hyrox training for long, lazy days on the links; the fitness races world championship, for which hed qualified, was just two weeks before he planned his world record attempt. So as he stayed in Hyrox training mode, he added in hundreds of hacks.

I would put a golf club next to my barbell or where I was doing lunges or pushing a sledthe second I finished my set, instead of resting, Id do constant air swings or hit plastic balls against a fence, he says. There were days when I had more than 500 swings in an hour span.

With his hands hardening to the task, Cokinos set his sights on the summer solstice. He planned to turn the longest day of the year into his longest day of golf.

Double Bogeys and Dodging Bears

His first shot plopped onto the green with a thud.

In the hours leading up to the event, Houstons skies had been swirling with storms. And Cokinos had been resting in the days before to save his energy, leaving him feeling buzzy and antsy. So a tee shot that landed 40 feet from the pin was a relief.

After running to the green, though, Cokinos got a taste of what his next 24 hours would feel like: He four-putted.

Im bellying a wedge [to putt], so its just one club the whole time, he says. Playing with a single club (Play smarter with TaylorMade Wedges) is common in speedgolf, the combination golf-and-running sport , where athletes try to combine fast times with low scores. Cokinos was playing, and putting, with a wedge, and had more than a few hours to get it right. But on the first hole, he was putting like Happy Gilmore. As he pulled the four-putted ball from the first hole, Cokinos thought, I have to do this 800 or 900 more times.

A Golf Shoe Unlike Any Other: We Hit the Links in the Footjoy Fury
Read More

Things would get a lot weirder than a double bogey, though. After night fell, Cokinos ran from the sixth green towards the seventh tee and was stopped in his tracks by a huge bear. Or, at least, thats what he thought it was.

Theres a big trash can thereand the way the shadow cast and the structure, it looked like a big old bear, he says. I had to remind myself, youre in Houston, Texas, in the middle of the city. Thats not a bear.

As the night wore on and he ran by this not-a-bear dozens of times, played hundreds of holes, and ate hundreds of energy gelshe might have wished for a bear attack.

The Turning Point

About 8 to 10 hours into this event, my knee was hurting. My stomach was hurting. I felt terrible, he says. Hed not only been taking hundreds of swings and logging dozens of miles. He also had to lean down after each shot to pick up his water and towel, bending over and standing up innumerable times.

So he lay down. He couldnt eat or drink anything, and felt like he was holding back vomit. Hes been eating energy gels, electrolyte (buy at Liquid I.V.) powders, and fruits for hours, aiming for 1500-2000 mg of sodium and 75-90 grams of carbs per hour. His knees, back, and shoulder ached. And he was lonely. Unlike during an ultramarathon or triathlon, where racers run by other runners who encourage each other, this was a solo event. There was an aid station every nine holes, but Cokinos was mostly alone with his thoughts and his club.

Hed already broken Byrnes record. And no one would care if he quit. No one, that is, except himself.

One of my pet peeves is when people talk about doing something big and they fall short, and still want a pat on the backand I was turning into that person right there as I lay on the ground, he says. He had, after all, said hed play 800 or 900 holes. He stayed on the ground, with his feet elevated on a chair, for about 20 total minutes before the nausea subsided and he could run again. If you just keep going at these types of eventsif youre able to push through 10 to 15 minutes of uncomfortable time, the storm shall pass.

These 2 Simple Workouts Can Improve Your VO2 Max in Record Time for HYROX and Beyond

It did. And Cokinos rose, ran, and asked his wife to grab some burgers, fries, and pizzas to fuel him instead of the gels and performance foods hed been eating.

In that beaten-up state, the idea of finishing a round and getting a bite of burger or pizzathat sound[ed] amazing, he said. Just suffer for 15 more minutes, and theres a great, greasy cheeseburger waiting for you.

Just Keep Swinging 

Twelve hours later, Cokinos was still swinging under the blazing Houston sun, thanks to the pizzas, burgers, and the kindness of a stranger who showed up halfway through his effort after seeing his record attempt being livestreamed on YouTube.

He finished off the last six hours with me, went six hours in a row. And we had the same routine every round to help keep me cool, Cokinos says. His angelic stranger would run along with him, carrying a water bottle and a towel. And at the courses sixth hole, Cokinos would hit a punch shot towards the green. Id throw my right arm out and hed hand me a water. Id lift my hat (snag a golf hat at Bonobos), pour water all over my face and neck, finish the bottle, and throw it at him. Hed throw me a towel so I could dry my hands.

It continued that way for six hoursarm out, bottle in and out, towel tossas he passed 700, then 800, and then 809 holes. Hed taken 2,875 strokes and approached the ninth tee. It was his 810th hole of golf since the previous evening.

Meet the Climber Setting Speed Records on the World's Highest Peaks
Read More

My shoulders were whacked, he says. But there were about 100 spectators standing behind the nearby green. I put the ball down and said a little prayer: God, help me get this ball in the air. Help this be the last great shot we hit today.

His prayer was answered: A breeze blew behind his ball, Cokinos says, and the ball landed three feet from the pin.

Its the moment you fantasize and dream about in your mind as you get ready for this thing, he says. Everyones yelling and cheering, and your support crews debating whether they should hug you or not, because youre so sweaty and disgusting.

As the ball hit the bottom of the cup, Cokinos had broken the Guinness record: Hed taken 2,878 strokes across 92 miles of running, completing 810 holes90 rounds of nine holesin 24 hours.

Redefining Whats Possible

But why?

Sure, he raised nearly $100,000 for Camp Aranzazu, a Texas camp where children with physical, mental, and emotional challenges can participate in accessible outdoor experiences. And yes, hed made some killer YouTube content.

But that wasnt the sole reason he wanted to complete the challenge; it was about showing up for himself in a way he didnt think was possible.

I think were all capable of a lot more than we think in our heads, he says. We set ceilings for ourselvesI thought I could never do a half-marathon. I did that, and I thought, man, I think I can push my body a little further. And so Ive constantly pushed this feeling of what Im capable of.

Cokinos advice to other guys is to find a way to push their ceilings higher.

If it scares you or intimidates you, and you cant sleep and youre thinking about it throughout the daythats probably a scary enough goal, he says. You can do more. You can push your body further. You can get closer to discomfort and still come out the other side victorious.
